# Architecture Rules

## Core Architecture
Use strict separation of concerns:

- UI
- state
- business logic
- persistence
- authorization

Do not mix these layers.

---

## Frontend Rules
- Use Next.js App Router
- Use feature-based architecture
- Use TypeScript
- Use Tailwind + shadcn/ui
- Mobile-first only

Do not build desktop-first layouts.

---

## Feature Boundaries
Organize code by feature domain.

Use:
- features/auth
- features/household
- features/budgets
- features/transactions
- features/recurring
- features/dashboard
- features/insights

Do not organize business logic globally by file type.

---

## Component Rules
Components are UI only.

Components must not:
- contain business logic
- call Supabase directly
- contain authorization logic
- contain complex mutation logic

Components render UI only.

---

## Data Access Rules
Components must never query or mutate Supabase directly.

Always use:
- feature services
- feature hooks

Business logic belongs in services.

---

## State Rules
Use:
- TanStack Query for server state
- Zustand for client app state
- React Hook Form + Zod for forms

Never:
- store server state in Zustand
- manage forms in Zustand

---

## Auth Rules
- Supabase Auth handles authentication
- Household membership handles authorization
- Never mix auth and permissions
- Never rely on frontend-only authorization

Authorization must be enforced in backend and RLS.

---

## Permission Rules
Never hardcode role checks in UI.

Never do:
- role === "owner"

Always use capabilities:
- canInviteMember
- canEditBudget
- canCloseMonth
- canAddExpense

Role resolution must be centralized.

---

## Backend Rules
Supabase is source of truth.

Supabase owns:
- auth
- persistence
- storage
- RLS
- security

Frontend is only a client.

---

## Audit Rules
All meaningful financial mutations must be auditable.

Never skip audit for:
- budget approval
- budget adjustment
- reallocation
- transaction edit
- transaction delete
- month close
- recurring toggle